:YeastPathways_PWY3O-15
        a                   owl:NamedIndividual , obo:GO_0006031 ;
        rdfs:comment        "Chitin, a linear polymer of N-acetyl glucosamine (GlcNAc) residues joined by beta-(1,4) linkages, is a minor but essential structural component of fungal cell walls. The majority (90%) of chitin in the cell wall is synthesized by chitin synthase III (CSIII), one of the three chitin synthases in S. cerevisiae (as reviewed in |CITS:[8257107]|). Each of the three chitin synthases (CSI, CSII, and CSIII) are nonessential, but the lack of all three leads to cell lethality (|CITS:[2050738]|). The genes encoding the catalytic subunits of CSI, CSII, and CSIII are CHS1, CHS2, and CHS3, respectively. Skt5p (Chs4/Cal2/Csd4) has been shown to physically interact with Chs3p, and is indispensable for its enzymatic activity in vivo (|CITS:[ 17142567]|). Chitin is deacetylated to form chitosan, a component of the yeast spore wall (ascospore)." ;
        rdfs:label          "chitin biosynthesis" ;
        dc:contributor      "GOC:sgd_curators" ;
        dc:date             "2023-09-14" ;
        pav:providedBy      "http://www.yeastgenome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "YeastPathways_PWY3O-15" ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

